  "response": "Okay, here are some well-regarded gay romance movies, spanning a range of tones and styles:\n\n**Classics & Groundbreakers:**\n\n*   **Brokeback Mountain (2005):**  A complex and tragic love story between two cowboys in 1960s America.  A landmark film for LGBTQ+ representation in mainstream cinema.\n*   **Maurice (1987):**  A Merchant Ivory adaptation of E.M. Forster's novel about a gay man's journey of self-discovery in Edwardian England. Beautifully shot and acted.\n*   **Beautiful Thing (1996):**  A sweet and charming coming-of-age story set in a working-class London neighborhood, focusing on the developing relationship between two teenage boys.\n*    **My Beautiful Laundrette (1985):** A British-Pakistani man and his former school friend start a laundrette together in London.\n*   **Another Country (1984):** Loosely based on the early life of spy Guy Burgess, this movie explores themes of sexuality and class at a British boarding school.\n\n**Contemporary & Popular:**\n\n*   **Love, Simon (2018):**  A heartwarming and widely appealing coming-of-age story about a closeted high school student navigating his first love.  A mainstream success.\n*   **Call Me by Your Name (2017):**  A sensual and evocative coming-of-age story set in Italy during the summer of 1983, exploring the passionate relationship between a teenager and an older academic.\n*   **God's Own Country (2017):**  A raw and emotionally powerful film about a young farmer in rural England who finds solace and connection with a Romanian migrant worker.\n*   **Single All the Way (2021):** A charming Christmas rom-com about a man who brings his best friend home for the holidays to pretend to be his boyfriend, but feelings develop.\n*   **Red, White & Royal Blue (2023):**  A lighthearted and fun romantic comedy based on the popular novel, about the budding relationship between the son of the US President and a British prince.\n*   **Spoiler Alert (2022):** A dramedy based on the memoir of Michael Ausiello and his relationship with his husband, Kit Cowan, and Cowan's battle with terminal cancer.\n\n**Indie & Arthouse:**\n\n*   **Weekend (2011):**  A naturalistic and intimate portrayal of a 48-hour relationship between two men in Nottingham, England.  Highly acclaimed for its realism.\n*   **Yossi & Jagger (2002):**  An Israeli film about two soldiers in the Golan Heights who are secretly in love.  A poignant and moving story.\n*   **Shelter (2007):**  A surfer and aspiring artist in Southern California falls for his best friend's older brother.\n*    **Summertime (2015):** A French drama about a farmer's daughter from the French countryside who encounters a Parisian feminist activist in 1971 and falls in love.\n\n**Foreign Language:**\n\n*   **The Way He Looks (Hoje Eu Quero Voltar Sozinho) (2014) (Brazil):**  A sweet and tender story about a blind teenager navigating first love.\n*    **Geography Club (2013):** A group of high school students form a Geography Club to support each other.\n\n**Things to Consider When Choosing:**\n\n*   **Your preferred genre:**  Are you looking for something light and funny, deeply emotional, or thought-provoking?\n*   **Themes:**  Are you interested in coming-of-age stories, historical dramas, or contemporary romances?\n*   **Content:**  Some films may contain mature themes, explicit content, or deal with difficult issues.  Check reviews and ratings beforehand.\n\nThis list is just a starting point, and there are many other great gay romance movies out there. I recommend reading reviews and watching trailers to find something that appeals to you. Enjoy!\n",
